s perFb team TfD outcomeandFb competition TfD outcomeandFb cl TfD outcomeandFb rbr TfD outcome", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1999%E2%80%932000_Santosh_Trophy"}
{"title_page": "United Arab Emirates at the 2008 Summer Olympics", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{infobox country at games\n| NOC = UAE\n| NOCname = [[United Arab Emirates National Olympic Committee]]\n| games = Summer Olympics\n| year = 2008\n| flagcaption = [[Flag of the United Arab Emirates]]\n| oldcode = \n| website = {{url|www.uaenoc.ae }}&nbsp;{{in lang|ar|en}}\n| location = [[Beijing]]\n| competitors = '''8'''\n| sports = '''7'''\n| flagbearer = [[Maitha bint Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Maitha Al Maktoum]] (opening)<br> [[Omar Juma Al-Salfa|Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa]] (closing)\n| rank = \n| gold = 0\n| silver = 0\n| bronze = 0\n| officials = \n| appearances = auto\n| app_begin_year = 1984\n| app_end_year = \n| summerappearances = \n| winterappearances = \n| seealso = \n}}\nThe [[United Arab Emirates]] participated at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], China, which were held from 8 to 24 August 2008. The country's participation at the Beijing Olympics marked its seventh appearance in the Summer Olympics since its d\u00e9but at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]]. The delegation sent by the [[United Arab Emirates National Olympic Committee]] consisted of eight athletes in seven sports: athletics, equestrian, judo, sailing, shooting, swimming and taekwondo. Two of the eight athletes were women, making Beijing the first time the country had sent female athletes to an Summer Olympiad, and most of their athletes qualified for the Games by using a [[Wild card (sports)|wild card]] or receiving an invitation from the Tripartite Commission. The country did not win any medals at the Games; the best performance of the delegation was from sport shooter [[Ahmed Al-Maktoum (sport shooter)|Ahmad Al-Makotum]], who placed seventh in the qualification round of the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double trap|men's double trap]] and lost a subsequent four-man shoot-out.\n\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n==Background==\nThe [[United Arab Emirates National Olympic Committee]] was recognised by the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) on 1 January 1980.<ref name=UAEIOC>{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates \u2013 National Olympic Committee (NOC)|url=https://www.olympic.org/united-arab-emirates|publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326041034/https://www.olympic.org/united-arab-emirates/|archive-date=26 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The nation made its debut at the Olympic Games four years later at the [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles Summer Olympics]], and has taken part in every Summer Olympics since, making Beijing their seventh appearance in a Summer Olympiad.<ref name=\"UAEOverview\">{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/UAE/|publisher=[[Sports Reference]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820163401/https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/UAE/|archive-date=20 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> {{As of|2020|}}, it has never participated in a [[Winter Olympic Games]].<ref name=\"UAEOverview\" /> The country has won a single medal, a [[gold medal]] in the sport of [[Shooting sports|shooting]].<ref name=\"UAEOverview\" /> The 2008 Summer Olympics were held from 8\u201324 August 2008; a total of 10,942 athletes represented 204 [[National Olympic Committees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/beijing-2008|title=Beijing 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 results & video highlights|publisher=International Olympic Committee|accessdate=13 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808185306/https://www.olympic.org/beijing-2008|archive-date=8 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In April 2008, the United Arab Emirates National Olympic Committee announced its largest delegation of athletes to an Olympic Games in sixteen years, with eight for Beijing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ali|first=Sayed|title=UAE to send biggest ever contingent|url=http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/08/04/03/10202669.html|newspaper=[[Gulf Times]]|date=3 April 2008|accessdate=25 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410070651/http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/08/04/03/10202669.html|archivedate=10 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> They were sprinter [[Omar Juma Al-Salfa|Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa]], equestrian rider [[Latifa bint Ahmed Al Maktoum|Latifah bint Ahmed Al Maktoum]], judoka [[Saeed Rashid Al Qubaisi]], sailor [[Adil Mohammad]], shooters [[Ahmed Al-Maktoum (sport shooter)|Ahmad Al Maktoum]] and [[Saeed bin Maktoum bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Saeed Al Maktoum]], short-distance swimmer [[Obaid Al-Jasmi|Obaid Al Jasmi]] and taekwondo [[Maitha bint Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Maitha Al Maktoum]].<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\">{{cite news|title=Gunning for glory: UAE at the Games|url=https://www.emirates247.com/gunning-for-glory-uae-at-the-games-2008-08-08-1.224311|publisher=[[Emirates 24/7]]|date=8 August 2008|accessdate=25 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052131/http://www.emirates247.com/gunning-for-glory-uae-at-the-games-2008-08-08-1.224311|archive-date=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> All the athletes were promised monetary awards of $272,000 should they win a gold medal, $200,000 for earning a [[silver medal]] and $136,000 for taking a [[bronze medal]].<ref name=\"AthletesOverview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/-272-000-bonus-for-uae-olympic-golds-45891.html|title=$272,000 bonus for UAE Olympic golds|last=Ferris-Lay|first=Claire|date=31 July 2008|newspaper=[[Arabian Business]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928043932/https://www.arabianbusiness.com/-272-000-bonus-for-uae-olympic-golds-45891.html|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The inclusion of Latifah and Matiha Al Maktoum marked the first time the United Arab Emirates had sent female athletes to an Olympic Games.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-wallechinsky/should-saudi-arabia-be-ba_b_115736.html?guccounter=1|title=Should Saudi Arabia be Banned from the Olympics?|last=Wallechinsky|first=David|date=6 August 2008|newspaper=[[HuffPost|Huffington Post]]|accessdate=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929084626/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-wallechinsky/should-saudi-arabia-be-ba_b_115736.html?guccounter=1|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Maitha Al Makotum was selected the flag bearer for the [[2008 Summer Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony]],<ref name=\"OpeningCeremony\">{{cite news|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395228145216|title=Sheikha Maitha Bint Mohammed bin Rashid to hoist UAE flag at Beijing 2008 Olympic Games|date=25 June 2008|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928173549/http://wam.ae/en/details/1395228145216|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live|agency=[[Emirates News Agency]]}}</ref> while Al-Salfa carried it at the [[2008 Summer Olympics closing ceremony|closing ceremony]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stillmed.olympic.org/Documents/Reports/EN/en_report_1362.pdf|title=List of Flagbearers Beijing 2008 \u2013 Closing Ceremony|publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815051849/https://stillmed.olympic.org/Documents/Reports/EN/en_report_1362.pdf|archive-date=15 August 2016|url-status=live|access-date=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{main|Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n[[File:Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfai 200 m Berlin 2009 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Omar Juma Al-Salfa|Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa]] ''(pictured in 2009)'' was the only athletics competitor for the United Arab Emirates in Beijing.]]\n\nAt the age of 18, Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa was the only athlete representing the United Arab Emirates in athletics competition.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/olympics-are-salfa-s-stepping-stone-1.561531?videoId=5770738884001|title=Olympics are Salfa's stepping stone|last=Rizvi|first=Ahmed|date=4 August 2008|newspaper=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928003329/https://www.thenational.ae/sport/olympics-are-salfa-s-stepping-stone-1.561531?videoId=5770738884001|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Beijing was his only appearance in the Olympic Games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/omar-al-salfa-1.html|title=Omar Al-Salfa Bio, Stats, and Results|publisher=Sports Reference|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923160309/https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/omar-al-salfa-1.html|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live|access-date=26 September 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Al-Salfa qualified for the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|men's 200 metres]] by using a [[Wild card (sports)|wildcard]] as the best non qualifying athlete for his country, because his personal best time of 20.94 seconds was 0.19 seconds slower than the \"B\" qualifying standard for the discipline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/OLY08/standards/index.html|title=Entry Standards \u2013 The XXIX Olympic Games - Beijing, China \u2013 8/24 August 2008|publisher=[[World Athletics|IAAF]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913131730/http://www.iaaf.org/OLY08/standards/index.html|archivedate=13 September 2008|accessdate=4 August 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"AlSalfaPrep\">{{cite news|last=Alvares|first=Rohan|title=Olympics: Al Salfa on right track|url=http://www.xpress4me.com:80/sport/uae/athletics/20009020.html|newspaper=[[XPRESS (newspaper)|XPRESS]]|date=7 August 2008|accessdate=25 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080808210722/http://www.xpress4me.com:80/sport/uae/athletics/20009020.html|archivedate=8 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> He spent six weeks preparing for the Games at a training camp in Poland with the team's national coach Vasko Anguelov Dimov.<ref name=\":0\" /> Al-Salfa said his objective was to improve his personal best and to reach the second round of the contest, saying, \"I must do something good at this Olympics. If I don\u2019t, I will not be happy.\"<ref name=\"AlSalfaPrep\" /> On 18 August, he was placed in heat seven of the men's 200 metres. Al-Salfa finished seventh and last out of all the finishing sprinters with a time of 21 seconds. Only the top three from a heat and the eight next fastest overall from all ten heats were allowed to advance to the second round, and Al-Salfa was eliminated since he was 40th overall.{{#tag:ref|Three athletes did not finish and one failed to start.<ref name=M200Results/>|group=\"n\"}}<ref name=\"M200Results\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=207|title=2008 Summer Olympics Results \u2013 Track and Field \u2013 Men's 200m results|publisher=[[ESPN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130143933/http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=207|archive-date=30 January 2017|url-status=live|access-date=7 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Key\n*'''Note'''\u2013Ranks given for track events are within the athlete's heat only\n*'''NR''' = National record\n</small>\n\n;Men\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=\"2\"|Heat\n!colspan=\"2\"|Quarterfinal\n!colspan=\"2\"|Semifinal\n!colspan=\"2\"|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Omar Juma Al-Salfa|Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa]]\n|align=left|[[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200 m]]\n|21.00\n|7\n|colspan=6|Did not advance<ref name=\"M200Results\" />\n|}\n\n==Equestrian==\n{{main|Equestrian at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[File:Beijing2008 eq medal jumping indiv01.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Hong Kong Sports Institute]], where Shaikha Latifah Bint Ahmad Bin Juma Al Maktoum took part in show jumping competition.]]\n\n[[Latifa bint Ahmed Al Maktoum|Shaikha Latifah Bint Ahmad Bin Juma Al Maktoum]] was 22 years old at the time of the Beijing Summer Games, and was making her only appearance in an Olympic Games.<ref name=LAMOverview>{{cite web|title=Latifah Al-Maktoum Bio, Stats, and Results|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/latifah-al-maktoum-1.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=26 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708211711/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/latifah-al-maktoum-1.html|archive-date=8 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She automatically qualified for the [[Equestrian at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Individual jumping|women's individual jumping contest]] because her time of 47.72 seconds at the Seventh Qatar International Show Jumping Championship in March 2007 was sufficient to make the Games. Latifah Al Maktoum missed the [[2007 Pan Arab Games]] in [[Cairo]] to focus on training for the Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tregoning|first=Sarah|title=UAE's Shaikha Latifa primed for success|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/uae-s-shaikha-latifa-primed-for-success-1.118338|newspaper=Gulf News|date=15 July 2008|accessdate=26 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617170703/https://gulfnews.com/sport/uae-s-shaikha-latifa-primed-for-success-1.118338|archive-date=17 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Before the Games, she said of her performance at the show jumping event in Qatar, \"I was under tremendous pressure in the first two rounds and it is always difficult to perform under pressure. It wasn't an easy course, as we saw not many riders get through, but in the end all that matters is the qualifier for the Olympics and I have done it.\"<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/>\n\nDuring the first part of the August 15 preliminary round, Latifah Al Maktoum and her horse Kalska De Semilly accrued eight penalty points from jump penalties and three points from time penalties, earning eleven penalty points overall.<ref name=LAMOverview/> Of the 77 competitors in this first portion of the event, she tied with [[Saudi Arabia at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Saudi Arabia]]'s [[Faisal Al-Shalan]] and [[Kamal Bahamdan]] for 61st overall.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|title=Individual Jumping 1st Qualifier \u2013 Friday, August 15, 2008 \u2013 HK Equestrian Venue (Shatin)|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/equestrian/resultsandschedules/rsc=EQX002900/index.html|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|accessdate=26 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517094713/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/equestrian/resultsandschedules/rsc=EQX002900/index.html|archivedate=17 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the second round, the pair accrued twelve jumping penalty points and three for time penalties.<ref name=LAMOverview/> This placed Latifah Al Maktoum 54th out of 70 finishing riders, tying Bahamdan and [[Bruce Goodin]] of [[New Zealand at the 2008 Summer Olympics|New Zealand]], and she was eliminated from the competition.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=723|title=2008 Summer Olympics Results \u2013 Equestrian \u2013 Individual Jumping Results|publisher=ESPN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928003405/http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=723|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Show jumping===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Horse\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Event\n!colspan=\"8\"|Qualification\n!colspan=\"5\"|Final\n!rowspan=2 colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!colspan=\"2\"|Round 1\n!colspan=\"3\"|Round 2\n!colspan=\"3\"|Round 3\n!colspan=\"2\"|Round A\n!colspan=\"3\"|Round B\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Total \n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Total \n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Total\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Latifah bint Ahmed Al Maktoum]]\n|align=left|Kalska De Semilly\n|align=left|[[Equestrian at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Individual jumping|Individual]]\n|11\n|61\n|15\n|26\n|54<ref name=\"LAMOverview\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n|colspan=8|Did not advance\n|26\n|54<ref name=\":3\" />\n|}\n\n==Judo==\n{{main|Judo at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[File:USTB Gymnasium.jpg|thumb|Al Qubaisi competed as a judoka at the [[Beijing Science and Technology University Gymnasium]].]]\n\nThe United Arab Emirates selected Saeed Rashid Al Qubaisi as the athlete to take part in men's judo. At the time of the Beijing Summer Olympics, he was the youngest athlete to represent his country at the Beijing Games at the age of 18 and was the first Emirati judoka to compete in Olympic combat sports.<ref name=\"AthletesOverview\"/> Al Quabisi qualified to compete in the [[Judo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 73 kg|men's lightweight (\u221273kg) tournament]] after receiving an invitation from the Tripartite Commission to allow athletes from [[National Olympic Committee]]s with small delegations to enter the Games.<ref name=Judo08BeijingAthletes>{{cite web|title=International Judo Federation \u2013 Qualifications for the Olympic Games 2008|url=http://beijing.ijf.org/olympics.xls|publisher=[[International Judo Federation]]|format=XLS|date=27 July 2008|accessdate=26 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722064934/http://beijing.ijf.org/olympics.xls|archivedate=22 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.beijing2008.cn/upload/Qualification/ijf_detailed_e.pdf|title=Games of the XXIX Olympiad, Beijing 2008: International Judo Federation|date=December 2006|publisher=Olympic.org|page=2|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815173911/http://en.beijing2008.cn/upload/Qualification/ijf_detailed_e.pdf|archive-date=15 August 2008|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> He trained with the [[Tunisia at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Tunisian national judo team]] at the Abu Dhabi Combat Club and later visited training camps in [[Belarus]] and [[Tunisia]] to prepare for the Olympics.<ref name=\"QuabisiSuccess\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/qubaisi-stalks-success-script-1.545386|title=Qubaisi stalks success script|last=Rizvi|first=Ahmed|date=3 August 2008|newspaper=The National|accessdate=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929085626/https://www.thenational.ae/sport/qubaisi-stalks-success-script-1.545386|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Al Qubaisi said before the Games that he hoped to win the gold medal and felt ready,<ref name=QuabisiSuccess/> \"I feel proud and I will look to do my country proud. Like this I can be an example to many youngsters, that you can be an Olympian at 18.\"<ref name=\"AthletesOverview\"/> He was drawn to face [[Marlon August]] of [[South Africa at the 2008 Summer Olympics|South Africa]] in the Round of 32 at the [[Beijing Science and Technology University Gymnasium]] on 11 August. In the one-minute-and-27-second match, Al Qubaisi was thrown onto the mat by August, who won by an [[Ippon]] score, preventing Al Qubaisi from advancing further.<ref name=\"QuabisiDefeatGulf\">{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/judo-al-qubaisi-s-early-exit-1.457514|title=Judo: Al Qubaisi\u2019s early exit|date=11 August 2008|newspaper=Gulf News|accessdate=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928003406/https://gulfnews.com/sport/judo-al-qubaisi-s-early-exit-1.457514|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live|agency=XPRESS}}</ref><ref name=\"BusinessQuabisiLoss\">{{cite news|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/uae-teenager-misses-out-in-beijing-judo-45285.html|title=UAE teenager misses out in Beijing judo|last=Sambridge|first=Andy|date=11 August 2008|newspaper=Arabian Business|accessdate=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928173548/https://www.arabianbusiness.com/uae-teenager-misses-out-in-beijing-judo-45285.html|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!scope=\"col\"|Round of 32\n!scope=\"col\"|Round of 16\n!scope=\"col\"|Quarterfinals\n!scope=\"col\"|Semifinals\n!scope=\"col\"|Repechage 1\n!scope=\"col\"|Repechage 2\n!scope=\"col\"|Repechage 3\n!colspan=2|Final / {{abbr|BM|Bronze medal match}}\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Saeed Rashid Al Qubaisi]]\n|align=left|[[Judo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 73 kg|Men's \u221273 kg]]\n|align=center|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Marlon August|August]]|RSA|2008 Summer}} <br/> '''L''' 0000\u20131000\n|colspan=8|Did not advance<ref name=\"QuabisiDefeatGulf\" /><ref name=\"BusinessQuabisiLoss\" />\n|}\n\n==Sailing==\n{{main|Sailing at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\nAdil Mohammad was competing in his only Olympic Games and was 18 years old at the time of the Beijing Summer Olympics.<ref name=AdilSR>{{cite web|title=Adil Mohammad Bio, Stats, and Results|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mo/adil-mohammad-1.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701105913/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mo/adil-mohammad-1.html|archive-date=1 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was the first sailor from an Arab country to compete in the sport at the Olympics.<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> Mohammad qualified to take part in the [[Sailing at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Laser|men's laser sailing category]] after he was granted a wild card invitation by the Tripartite Commission.<ref name=mohammad-oly>{{cite news|first=Alaric|last=Gomes|title=Adel Khalid hopes for boost to his sport|url=http://gulfnews.com/sport/sailing/adel-khalid-hopes-for-boost-to-his-sport-1.643111|newspaper=Gulf News|date=19 June 2010|accessdate=9 July 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710090836/http://gulfnews.com/sport/sailing/adel-khalid-hopes-for-boost-to-his-sport-1.643111|archive-date=10 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He trained and competed in sailing competitions across Europe for seven months as preparation for the Games.<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> Before the Olympics, Mohammad spoke of his pride of representing the United Arab Emirates at the Olympics and stated he felt confident about winning the gold medal in his category: \"It is the dream of every athlete and sportsperson to compete in the Olympics. So it has been my dream as well. Now that I am going to Beijing, I feel proud of myself, I feel proud for my country and I hope to put the UAE on top of the world.\"<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> He competed in the one-person dinghy event, where he was assessed using a score derived from his participation in nine distinct races.<ref name=AdilSR/> In the first and second races, Mohammed finished 38th; in the third, 42nd; in the fourth, 43rd (and last); in the fifth, 11th (his highest); in the sixth, 36th; in the seventh, 42nd; in the eighth, 38th; and in the ninth, 27th. A tenth race was scheduled but cancelled.<ref name=\"ESPNSailing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=734|title=2008 Summer Olympics Results \u2013 Sailing \u2013 Men's \u2013 One person Dingy Results|publisher=ESPN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928173548/http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=734|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref> Overall, he ranked 42nd out of 43 sailors, earning a collective 272 points across all nine races.<ref name=ESPNSailing/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=11|Race\n!rowspan=2|Net points\n!rowspan=2|Final rank\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|1\n!scope=\"col\"|2\n!scope=\"col\"|3\n!scope=\"col\"|4\n!scope=\"col\"|5\n!scope=\"col\"|6\n!scope=\"col\"|7\n!scope=\"col\"|8\n!scope=\"col\"|9\n!scope=\"col\"|10\n!scope=\"col\"|M*\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Adil Mohammad]]\n|align=left|[[Sailing at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Laser|Laser]]\n|38\n|38\n|42\n|<s>43</s>\n|11\n|36\n|42\n|38\n|27\n|CAN\n|EL\n|272\n|42<ref name=\"ESPNSailing\" />\n|}\n<small>'''M''' = Medal race; EL = Eliminated \u2013 did not advance into the medal race; CAN = Race cancelled;</small>\n\n==Shooting==\n{{main|Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[File:Sheikh saeed bin maktoum al maktoum.jpg|thumb|right|Saeed Al Maktoum ''(pictured in 2016)'' represented the United Arab Emirates for the third time in Olympic shooting competition.]]\n\nThe oldest member of the team at the age of 44,<ref name=NIEAhmad>{{cite news|title=Al-Maktoum gearing up to defend his Olympic gold|url=http://www.newindpress.com/NewsItems.asp?ID=IEE20080730052916&Page=E&Title=Olympics+2008&Topic=0|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=15 August 2008|accessdate=27 September 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5a52tOwCe?url=http://www.newindpress.com/NewsItems.asp?ID%3DIEE20080730052916%26Page%3DE%26Title%3DOlympics%2B2008%26Topic%3D0|archivedate=15 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sheikh Ahmad Al-Makotum was making his third appearance at a Summer Olympiad, having previously represented the United Arab Emirates at the [[United Arab Emirates at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Summer Olympics]] and the [[United Arab Emirates at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Athens Olympic Games]].<ref name=\"ClayMay16\">{{cite news|url=http://www.clay-shooting.com/features/man-on-fire-how-royalty-in-the-uae-changed-britains-olympic-medal-future/|title=Man on fire \u2013 how royalty in the UAE changed Britain\u2019s Olympic-medal future|date=3 May 2016|newspaper=Clay Shooting|accessdate=27 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928173548/http://www.clay-shooting.com/features/man-on-fire-how-royalty-in-the-uae-changed-britains-olympic-medal-future/|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He won the nation's first gold medal in [[Shooting at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double trap|men's double trap]] at the 2004 Summer Olympics.<ref name=ClayMay16/> Ahmad Al-Makotum qualified for the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's trap|men's trap]] and [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double trap|double trap]] after winning two quota spots reserved by the [[International Shooting Sport Federation]] for athletes who met the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|minimum qualification scores]] of 112 and 118 points at the [[2005 World Shotgun Championships]] in [[Lonato del Garda]], Italy.<ref name=ClayMay16/><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.beijing2008.cn/upload/Qualification/issf_detailed_e.pdf|title=Games of the XXIX Olympiad, Beijing 2008: Shooting: International Shooting Sport Federation (ISSF)|date=December 2006|publisher=Olympic.org|pages=2\u20135|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815173850/http://en.beijing2008.cn/upload/Qualification/issf_detailed_e.pdf|archive-date=15 August 2008|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> He began his preparation for the Games two months beforehand,<ref name=NIEAhmad/> but said to ''[[The New Indian Express]]'' that he was not expecting to win anything in Beijing.<ref name=NIEAhmad/> On 9 August he competed in the qualification round of men's trap, finishing 30th out of 35 shooters with a score of 110. He equalled the score of [[Lee Wung Yew]] of [[Singapore at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Singapore]] and [[Ireland at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Ireland]]'s [[Derek Burnett]]. Ahmad Al-Makotum's tournament ended at the qualification round since he scored nine fewer points than the lowest-scoring qualifier.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Shooting at the 2008 Beijing Summer Games: Men's Trap Preliminary Round|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/2008/SHO/mens-trap-preliminary-round.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705110923/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/2008/SHO/mens-trap-preliminary-round.html|archive-date=5 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three days later, he took part in the qualifying round of the men's double trap, placing seventh out of nineteen competitors with a score of 136 points.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://cn.reuters.com/article/olympics-shooting-men-trap-qual-results-idCNISS83221320080812|title=Olympics-Shooting-Men's double trap qualification results|date=12 August 2008|access-date=29 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829083816/https://cn.reuters.com/article/olympics-shooting-men-trap-qual-results-idCNISS83221320080812|archive-date=29 August 2018|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> Ahmad Al-Makotum subsequently lost a four-way shoot-out to determine the sixth shooter to advance to the final between [[Australia at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Australia]]'s [[Russell Mark]], [[William Chetcuti]] of [[Malta at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Malta]] and [[Hungary at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Hungary]]'s [[Roland Gerebics]] since all four had the same score.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20080813/shooting/final-just-eludes-eighth-placed-chetcuti.220588|title=Final just eludes eighth-placed Chetcuti|date=13 August 2008|newspaper=[[Times of Malta]]|access-date=29 August 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816114357/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20080813/shooting/final-just-eludes-eighth-placed-chetcuti.220588|archive-date=16 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSheikh Saeed Al Maktoum was 31 years old at the time of the Beijing Olympics.<ref name=SaeedOverview>{{cite web|title=Sheikh Saeed Al-Maktoum Bio, Stats, and Results|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/sheikh-saeed-al-maktoum-1.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729051205/https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/sheikh-saeed-al-maktoum-1.html|archive-date=29 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also represented the United Arab Emirates at the 2000 Sydney Summer Games and the 2004 Athens Summer Olympics but did not medal.<ref name=SaeedOverview/> Saeed Al Maktoum earned automatic qualification for the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's skeet|men's skeet]] because he met the minimum qualification score of 114 points in the category at the [[2007 Asian Shooting Championships]] in [[Kuwait City]], Kuwait, where he won the bronze medal.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=SaeedXinhua>{{cite news|title=Dubai Crown Prince Al Maktoum Saeed eyes a medal at Olympics|url=http://www.china.org.cn/olympic/2008-07/30/content_16098413.htm|publisher=[[China Internet Information Center]]|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=30 July 2008|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219062541/http://www.china.org.cn/olympic/2008-07/30/content_16098413.htm|archive-date=19 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He began his training for his tournament after arriving in Beijing on 26 July.<ref name=SaeedXinhua/> Saeed Al Maktoum said of his chances, \"I have confidence in my capability, but I haven't got used to the shooting range yet. There are many ups and downs at the back (mountains). But in our country, the range is flat. We believe in God. If God gives you, nobody could take it away.\"<ref name=SaeedXinhua/> On 15 August he participated in the first heat of the qualification round of the men's skeet, finishing 22nd out of 41 participants with a score of 114 points.<ref name=\"ESPNMensSkeet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=298|title=2008 Summer Olympics Results \u2013 Shooting \u2013 Men's Skeet|publisher=ESPN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928043935/http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=298|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref> He scored seven fewer points than the highest-scoring athlete, [[Vincent Hancock]] of the [[United States at the 2008 Summer Olympics|United States]], and four fewer than the lowest scoring qualifier, [[Qu Ridong]] of [[China at the 2008 Summer Olympics|China]]; his competition thus ended at the qualifying round.<ref name=ESPNMensSkeet/> He would again represent the United Arab Emirates at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] and the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio Olympics]].<ref name=SaeedOverview/>\n\n;Men\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=2|Qualification\n!colspan=2|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Points\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Points\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left rowspan=2|[[Ahmed Al-Maktoum (sport shooter)|Ahmad Al Maktoum]]\n|align=left|[[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's trap|Trap]]\n|110\n|30\n|colspan=2| Did not advance<ref name=\":4\" />\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double trap|Double trap]]\n|136\n|7\n|colspan=2| Did not advance<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Saeed bin Maktoum bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Saeed Al Maktoum]]\n|align=left|[[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's skeet|Skeet]]\n|114\n|22\n|colspan=2| Did not advance<ref name=\"ESPNMensSkeet\" />\n|}\n\n==Swimming==\n{{main|Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[File:InsideWatercube.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Beijing National Aquatics Centre]], where Al Jasmi took part in swimming contests.]]\n\n27-year-old police officer Obaid Al Jasmi was competing in his second Olympic Games after representing the United Arab Emirates four years earlier at the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens.<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> Although his best time of 53.70 seconds was 2.75 seconds slower than the \"B\" (FINA/Olympic) qualifying time for the event, he entered the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|men's 100 metres freestyle]] after being granted a universality place that was issued to swimmers who did not qualify on merit from the world governing body of swimming, [[FINA]].<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swimswam.com/fina-announces-qualifying-standards-for-london-2012/|title=FINA Announces Qualifying Standards for London 2012|last=Keith|first=Branden|date=25 November 2010|publisher=[[SwimSwam]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020001240/https://swimswam.com/fina-announces-qualifying-standards-for-london-2012/|archivedate=20 October 2016|access-date=17 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Environment\">{{cite web|url=http://fina.org/events/OG/Beijing_2008/pdf/qualifyingprocedures_sw.pdf|title=Olympic Qualifying Procedures for Swimming|publisher=[[FINA]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070304105903/http://www.fina.org/events/OG/Beijing_2008/pdf/qualifyingprocedures_sw.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=4 March 2007|accessdate=2007-03-20}}</ref> Al Jasmi had less than two months to prepare for the Games.<ref name=ALShinMag84/> He set himself the objective of improving his personal best time at the Olympics but noted the strong competition he would face.<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> On 12 August, Al Jasmi competed in the six-swimmer heat two of the contest.<ref name=Men100Freestyle>{{cite web|title=2008 Beijing Summer Olympics \u2013 Swimming \u2013 Men's 100m Freestyle|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/swimming/resultsandschedules/rsc=SWM011900/index.html|publisher=NBC Sports|accessdate=27 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517044815/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/swimming/resultsandschedules/rsc=SWM011900/index.html|archivedate=17 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He placed last with a new [[List of Emirates records in swimming|national-record]] time of 53.29 seconds.<ref name=ALShinMag84>{{cite journal|last=Gonzaga|first=Andre|title=Yet Another Olympic Games: More Lessons to be Learnt|url=https://www.alshindagah.com/Shindagah84/sport_1.htm|journal=Al Shindagah|issue=84|date=October 2008|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220025534/http://www.alshindagah.com/Shindagah84/sport_1.htm|archive-date=20 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Men100Freestyle/> Al Jasmi ranked 61st out of 64 swimmers overall and did not advance into the semi-finals since the format of the tournament only allowed for the progression of the top sixteen overall finishers.{{#tag:ref|One swimmer, [[Milorad \u010cavi\u0107]], withdrew from the tournament.<ref name=Men100Freestyle/>|group=\"n\"}}<ref name=Men100Freestyle/> After the Olympics, he spoke of his satisfaction of his performance: \"I benefited greatly from my participation in the Olympic Games and succeeded in bettering my personal record and I am looking forward to taking part in the GCC Championships and I am determined to achieve good results.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/swimming/obaid-keen-to-improve-form-1.125862|title=Obaid keen to improve form|last=Abbasher|first=Yasir|date=20 August 2008|newspaper=Gulf News|accessdate=27 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928003358/https://gulfnews.com/sport/swimming/obaid-keen-to-improve-form-1.125862|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n;Men\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=\"2\"|Heat\n!colspan=\"2\"|Semifinal\n!colspan=\"2\"|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Time\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Time\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Time\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Obaid Al-Jasmi|Obaid Al Jasmi]]\n|align=left|[[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]\n|53.29 '''[[List of Emirates records in swimming|NR]]'''\n|61\n|colspan=4|Did not advance<ref name=\"ALShinMag84\" /><ref name=\"Men100Freestyle\" />\n|}\n\n==Taekwondo==\n{{main|Taekwondo at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\nSheikha Maitha Al Maktoum was 28 years old at the time of the Beijing Summer Olympics and was making her debut appearance in the Olympic Games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maitha Al-Maktoum Bio, Stats, and Results|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/maitha-al-maktoum-1.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708042333/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/maitha-al-maktoum-1.html|archive-date=8 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She was announced as a qualified competitor for the [[Taekwondo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 67 kg|women's middleweight (\u221267kg) taekwondo competition]] after the IOC cleared her to participate following the allocation of quota places for athletes deemed to have \"an extraordinary record in their sporting discipline.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Gomes|first=Alaric|title=Shaika Maitha bound for Beijing Olympics|url=http://archive.gulfnews.com/indepth/olympics08/sports/10199968.html|newspaper=Gulf Times|date=24 March 2008|accessdate=27 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620232311/http://archive.gulfnews.com/indepth/olympics08/sports/10199968.html|archivedate=20 June 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Maitha Al Maktoum trained at the [[Kyung Hee University]] in the South Korean capital city of [[Seoul]] to prepare for the Games.<ref name=\"KTPrincess\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/people/2013/08/178_28790.html|title=UAE Princess Will Compete in Taekwondo at Beijing Olympics|last=Se-jeong|first=Kim|date=5 August 2008|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929090302/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/people/2013/08/178_28790.html|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She said before the Olympics, \"Everybody who is going to compete in Beijing is going there to win and I am no exception. I have to respect them all. They have all dedicated themselves to this and the only thing they want is a medal. I am the same though and I will have to match their focus if I am to succeed.\"<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> Maitha Al Maktoum faced [[South Korea at the 2008 Summer Olympics|South Korea]]'s [[Hwang Kyung-seon]] in the Round of 16 on 22 August. She lost to her opponent 5\u20131 in points and was defeated 4\u20130 in her [[repechage]] match against [[Sandra \u0160ari\u0107]] of [[Croatia at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Croatia]], ending her chance of a bronze medal.<ref name=\"MatchShaikka\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/uae-sheikha-kicked-in-her-face-in-taekwondo-debut-295590.html|title=UAE sheikha kicked in her face in taekwondo debut|date=22 August 2008|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929090548/https://www.news18.com/news/india/uae-sheikha-kicked-in-her-face-in-taekwondo-debut-295590.html|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live|publisher=[[CNN-News18]]}}</ref> After the tournament, Matiha Al Maktoum stated, \"It's a dream and a nightmare at the same time. I couldn't wait until it was going to happen. And now I can't believe it's over. I think I performed well for what my background is and my experience.\"<ref name=MatchShaikka/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!scope=\"col\"|Round of 16\n!scope=\"col\"|Quarterfinals\n!scope=\"col\"|Semifinals\n!scope=\"col\"|Repechage \n!scope=\"col\"|Bronze Medal\n!colspan=2|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Maitha bint Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Maitha Al Maktoum]]\n|align=left|[[Taekwondo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 67 kg|Women's \u221267 kg]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Hwang Kyung-Seon|Hwang K-S]]|KOR|2008 Summer}}<br/>'''L''' 1\u20135\n|colspan=2|Did not advance\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Sandra \u0160ari\u0107|\u0160ari\u0107]]|CRO|2008 Summer}}<br/> '''L''' 0\u20134\n|colspan=3|Did not advance<ref name=\"MatchShaikka\" />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[United Arab Emirates at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|30em|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Nations at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Portal bar|Olympics|United Arab Emirates}}\n\n[[Category:Nations at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:United Arab Emirates at the Summer Olympics by year|2008]]\n[[Category:2008 in Emirati sport|Olympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{infobox country at games\n| NOC = UAE\n| NOCname = [[United Arab Emirates National Olympic Committee]]\n| games = Summer Olympics\n| year = 2008\n| flagcaption = [[Flag of the United Arab Emirates]]\n| oldcode = \n| website = {{url|www.uaenoc.ae }}&nbsp;{{in lang|ar|en}}\n| location = [[Beijing]]\n| competitors = '''8'''\n| sports = '''7'''\n| flagbearer = [[Maitha bint Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Maitha Al Maktoum]] (opening)<br> [[Omar Juma Al-Salfa|Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa]] (closing)\n| rank = \n| gold = 0\n| silver = 0\n| bronze = 0\n| officials = \n| appearances = auto\n| app_begin_year = 1984\n| app_end_year = \n| summerappearances = \n| winterappearances = \n| seealso = \n}}\nThe [[United Arab Emirates]] participated at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], China, which were held from 8 to 24 August 2008. The country's participation at the Beijing Olympics marked its seventh appearance in the Summer Olympics since its d\u00e9but at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]]. The delegation sent by the [[United Arab Emirates National Olympic Committee]] consisted of eight athletes in seven sports: athletics, equestrian, judo, sailing, shooting, swimming and taekwondo. Two of the eight athletes were women, making Beijing the first time the country had sent female athletes to an Summer Olympiad, and most of their athletes qualified for the Games by using a [[Wild card (sports)|wild card]] or receiving an invitation from the Tripartite Commission. The country did not win any medals at the Games; the best performance of the delegation was from sport shooter [[Ahmed Al-Maktoum (sport shooter)|Ahmad Al-Makotum]], who placed seventh in the qualification round of the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double trap|men's double trap]] and lost a subsequent four-man shoot-out.\n\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n==Background==\nThe [[United Arab Emirates National Olympic Committee]] was recognised by the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) on 1 January 1980.<ref name=UAEIOC>{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates \u2013 National Olympic Committee (NOC)|url=https://www.olympic.org/united-arab-emirates|publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326041034/https://www.olympic.org/united-arab-emirates/|archive-date=26 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The nation made its debut at the Olympic Games four years later at the [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles Summer Olympics]], and has taken part in every Summer Olympics since, making Beijing their seventh appearance in a Summer Olympiad.<ref name=\"UAEOverview\">{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/UAE/|publisher=[[Sports Reference]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820163401/https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/UAE/|archive-date=20 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> {{As of|2020|}}, it has never participated in a [[Winter Olympic Games]].<ref name=\"UAEOverview\" /> The country has won a single medal, a [[gold medal]] in the sport of [[Shooting sports|shooting]].<ref name=\"UAEOverview\" /> The 2008 Summer Olympics were held from 8\u201324 August 2008; a total of 10,942 athletes represented 204 [[National Olympic Committees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/beijing-2008|title=Beijing 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 results & video highlights|publisher=International Olympic Committee|accessdate=13 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808185306/https://www.olympic.org/beijing-2008|archive-date=8 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In April 2008, the United Arab Emirates National Olympic Committee announced its largest delegation of athletes to an Olympic Games in sixteen years, with eight for Beijing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ali|first=Sayed|title=UAE to send biggest ever contingent|url=http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/08/04/03/10202669.html|newspaper=[[Gulf Times]]|date=3 April 2008|accessdate=25 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410070651/http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/08/04/03/10202669.html|archivedate=10 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> They were sprinter [[Omar Juma Al-Salfa|Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa]], equestrian rider [[Latifa bint Ahmed Al Maktoum|Latifah bint Ahmed Al Maktoum]], judoka [[Saeed Rashid Al Qubaisi]], sailor [[Adil Mohammad]], shooters [[Ahmed Al-Maktoum (sport shooter)|Ahmad Al Maktoum]] and [[Saeed bin Maktoum bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Saeed Al Maktoum]], short-distance swimmer [[Obaid Al-Jasmi|Obaid Al Jasmi]] and taekwondo [[Maitha bint Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Maitha Al Maktoum]].<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\">{{cite news|title=Gunning for glory: UAE at the Games|url=https://www.emirates247.com/gunning-for-glory-uae-at-the-games-2008-08-08-1.224311|publisher=[[Emirates 24/7]]|date=8 August 2008|accessdate=25 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052131/http://www.emirates247.com/gunning-for-glory-uae-at-the-games-2008-08-08-1.224311|archive-date=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> All the athletes were promised monetary awards of $272,000 should they win a gold medal, $200,000 for earning a [[silver medal]] and $136,000 for taking a [[bronze medal]].<ref name=\"AthletesOverview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/-272-000-bonus-for-uae-olympic-golds-45891.html|title=$272,000 bonus for UAE Olympic golds|last=Ferris-Lay|first=Claire|date=31 July 2008|newspaper=[[Arabian Business]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928043932/https://www.arabianbusiness.com/-272-000-bonus-for-uae-olympic-golds-45891.html|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The inclusion of Latifah and Matiha Al Maktoum marked the first time the United Arab Emirates had sent female athletes to an Olympic Games.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-wallechinsky/should-saudi-arabia-be-ba_b_115736.html?guccounter=1|title=Should Saudi Arabia be Banned from the Olympics?|last=Wallechinsky|first=David|date=6 August 2008|newspaper=[[HuffPost|Huffington Post]]|accessdate=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929084626/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-wallechinsky/should-saudi-arabia-be-ba_b_115736.html?guccounter=1|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Maitha Al Makotum was selected the flag bearer for the [[2008 Summer Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony]],<ref name=\"OpeningCeremony\">{{cite news|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395228145216|title=Sheikha Maitha Bint Mohammed bin Rashid to hoist UAE flag at Beijing 2008 Olympic Games|date=25 June 2008|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928173549/http://wam.ae/en/details/1395228145216|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live|agency=[[Emirates News Agency]]}}</ref> while Al-Salfa carried it at the [[2008 Summer Olympics closing ceremony|closing ceremony]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stillmed.olympic.org/Documents/Reports/EN/en_report_1362.pdf|title=List of Flagbearers Beijing 2008 \u2013 Closing Ceremony|publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815051849/https://stillmed.olympic.org/Documents/Reports/EN/en_report_1362.pdf|archive-date=15 August 2016|url-status=live|access-date=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{main|Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n[[File:Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfai 200 m Berlin 2009 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Omar Juma Al-Salfa|Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa]] ''(pictured in 2009)'' was the only athletics competitor for the United Arab Emirates in Beijing.]]\n\nAt the age of 18, Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa was the only athlete representing the United Arab Emirates in athletics competition.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/olympics-are-salfa-s-stepping-stone-1.561531?videoId=5770738884001|title=Olympics are Salfa's stepping stone|last=Rizvi|first=Ahmed|date=4 August 2008|newspaper=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928003329/https://www.thenational.ae/sport/olympics-are-salfa-s-stepping-stone-1.561531?videoId=5770738884001|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Beijing was his only appearance in the Olympic Games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/omar-al-salfa-1.html|title=Omar Al-Salfa Bio, Stats, and Results|publisher=Sports Reference|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923160309/https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/omar-al-salfa-1.html|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live|access-date=26 September 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Al-Salfa qualified for the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|men's 200 metres]] by using a [[Wild card (sports)|wildcard]] as the best non qualifying athlete for his country, because his personal best time of 20.94 seconds was 0.19 seconds slower than the \"B\" qualifying standard for the discipline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/OLY08/standards/index.html|title=Entry Standards \u2013 The XXIX Olympic Games - Beijing, China \u2013 8/24 August 2008|publisher=[[World Athletics|IAAF]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913131730/http://www.iaaf.org/OLY08/standards/index.html|archivedate=13 September 2008|accessdate=4 August 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"AlSalfaPrep\">{{cite news|last=Alvares|first=Rohan|title=Olympics: Al Salfa on right track|url=http://www.xpress4me.com:80/sport/uae/athletics/20009020.html|newspaper=[[XPRESS (newspaper)|XPRESS]]|date=7 August 2008|accessdate=25 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080808210722/http://www.xpress4me.com:80/sport/uae/athletics/20009020.html|archivedate=8 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> He spent six weeks preparing for the Games at a training camp in Poland with the team's national coach Vasko Anguelov Dimov.<ref name=\":0\" /> Al-Salfa said his objective was to improve his personal best and to reach the second round of the contest, saying, \"I must do something good at this Olympics. If I don\u2019t, I will not be happy.\"<ref name=\"AlSalfaPrep\" /> On 18 August, he was placed in heat seven of the men's 200 metres. Al-Salfa finished seventh and last out of all the finishing sprinters with a time of 21 seconds. Only the top three from a heat and the eight next fastest overall from all ten heats were allowed to advance to the second round, and Al-Salfa was eliminated since he was 40th overall.{{#tag:ref|Three athletes did not finish and one failed to start.<ref name=M200Results/>|group=\"n\"}}<ref name=\"M200Results\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=207|title=2008 Summer Olympics Results \u2013 Track and Field \u2013 Men's 200m results|publisher=[[ESPN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130143933/http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=207|archive-date=30 January 2017|url-status=live|access-date=7 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Key\n*'''Note'''\u2013Ranks given for track events are within the athlete's heat only\n*'''NR''' = National record\n</small>\n\n;Men\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=\"2\"|Heat\n!colspan=\"2\"|Quarterfinal\n!colspan=\"2\"|Semifinal\n!colspan=\"2\"|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Omar Juma Al-Salfa|Omar Jouma Bilal Al-Salfa]]\n|align=left|[[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200 m]]\n|21.00\n|7\n|colspan=6|Did not advance<ref name=\"M200Results\" />\n|}\n\n==Equestrian==\n{{main|Equestrian at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[File:Beijing2008 eq medal jumping indiv01.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Hong Kong Sports Institute]], where Shaikha Latifah Bint Ahmad Bin Juma Al Maktoum took part in show jumping competition.]]\n\n[[Latifa bint Ahmed Al Maktoum|Shaikha Latifah Bint Ahmad Bin Juma Al Maktoum]] was 22 years old at the time of the Beijing Summer Games, and was making her only appearance in an Olympic Games.<ref name=LAMOverview>{{cite web|title=Latifah Al-Maktoum Bio, Stats, and Results|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/latifah-al-maktoum-1.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=26 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708211711/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/latifah-al-maktoum-1.html|archive-date=8 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She automatically qualified for the [[Equestrian at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Individual jumping|women's individual jumping contest]] because her time of 47.72 seconds at the Seventh Qatar International Show Jumping Championship in March 2007 was sufficient to make the Games. Latifah Al Maktoum missed the [[2007 Pan Arab Games]] in [[Cairo]] to focus on training for the Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tregoning|first=Sarah|title=UAE's Shaikha Latifa primed for success|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/uae-s-shaikha-latifa-primed-for-success-1.118338|newspaper=Gulf News|date=15 July 2008|accessdate=26 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617170703/https://gulfnews.com/sport/uae-s-shaikha-latifa-primed-for-success-1.118338|archive-date=17 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Before the Games, she said of her performance at the show jumping event in Qatar, \"I was under tremendous pressure in the first two rounds and it is always difficult to perform under pressure. It wasn't an easy course, as we saw not many riders get through, but in the end all that matters is the qualifier for the Olympics and I have done it.\"<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/>\n\nDuring the first part of the August 15 preliminary round, Latifah Al Maktoum and her horse Kalska De Semilly accrued eight penalty points from jump penalties and three points from time penalties, earning eleven penalty points overall.<ref name=LAMOverview/> Of the 77 competitors in this first portion of the event, she tied with [[Saudi Arabia at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Saudi Arabia]]'s [[Faisal Al-Shalan]] and [[Kamal Bahamdan]] for 61st overall.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|title=Individual Jumping 1st Qualifier \u2013 Friday, August 15, 2008 \u2013 HK Equestrian Venue (Shatin)|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/equestrian/resultsandschedules/rsc=EQX002900/index.html|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|accessdate=26 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517094713/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/equestrian/resultsandschedules/rsc=EQX002900/index.html|archivedate=17 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the second round, the pair accrued twelve jumping penalty points and three for time penalties.<ref name=LAMOverview/> This placed Latifah Al Maktoum 54th out of 70 finishing riders, tying Bahamdan and [[Bruce Goodin]] of [[New Zealand at the 2008 Summer Olympics|New Zealand]], and she was eliminated from the competition.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=723|title=2008 Summer Olympics Results \u2013 Equestrian \u2013 Individual Jumping Results|publisher=ESPN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928003405/http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=723|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Show jumping===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Horse\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Event\n!colspan=\"8\"|Qualification\n!colspan=\"5\"|Final\n!rowspan=2 colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!colspan=\"2\"|Round 1\n!colspan=\"3\"|Round 2\n!colspan=\"3\"|Round 3\n!colspan=\"2\"|Round A\n!colspan=\"3\"|Round B\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Total \n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Total \n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Total\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Penalties\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Latifah bint Ahmed Al Maktoum]]\n|align=left|Kalska De Semilly\n|align=left|[[Equestrian at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Individual jumping|Individual]]\n|11\n|61\n|15\n|26\n|54<ref name=\"LAMOverview\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n|colspan=8|Did not advance\n|26\n|54<ref name=\":3\" />\n|}\n\n==Judo==\n{{main|Judo at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[File:USTB Gymnasium.jpg|thumb|Al Qubaisi competed as a judoka at the [[Beijing Science and Technology University Gymnasium]].]]\n\nThe United Arab Emirates selected Saeed Rashid Al Qubaisi as the athlete to take part in men's judo. At the time of the Beijing Summer Olympics, he was the youngest athlete to represent his country at the Beijing Games at the age of 18 and was the first Emirati judoka to compete in Olympic combat sports.<ref name=\"AthletesOverview\"/> Al Quabisi qualified to compete in the [[Judo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 73 kg|men's lightweight (\u221273kg) tournament]] after receiving an invitation from the Tripartite Commission to allow athletes from [[National Olympic Committee]]s with small delegations to enter the Games.<ref name=Judo08BeijingAthletes>{{cite web|title=International Judo Federation \u2013 Qualifications for the Olympic Games 2008|url=http://beijing.ijf.org/olympics.xls|publisher=[[International Judo Federation]]|format=XLS|date=27 July 2008|accessdate=26 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722064934/http://beijing.ijf.org/olympics.xls|archivedate=22 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.beijing2008.cn/upload/Qualification/ijf_detailed_e.pdf|title=Games of the XXIX Olympiad, Beijing 2008: International Judo Federation|date=December 2006|publisher=Olympic.org|page=2|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815173911/http://en.beijing2008.cn/upload/Qualification/ijf_detailed_e.pdf|archive-date=15 August 2008|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> He trained with the [[Tunisia at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Tunisian national judo team]] at the Abu Dhabi Combat Club and later visited training camps in [[Belarus]] and [[Tunisia]] to prepare for the Olympics.<ref name=\"QuabisiSuccess\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/qubaisi-stalks-success-script-1.545386|title=Qubaisi stalks success script|last=Rizvi|first=Ahmed|date=3 August 2008|newspaper=The National|accessdate=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929085626/https://www.thenational.ae/sport/qubaisi-stalks-success-script-1.545386|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Al Qubaisi said before the Games that he hoped to win the gold medal and felt ready,<ref name=QuabisiSuccess/> \"I feel proud and I will look to do my country proud. Like this I can be an example to many youngsters, that you can be an Olympian at 18.\"<ref name=\"AthletesOverview\"/> He was drawn to face [[Marlon August]] of [[South Africa at the 2008 Summer Olympics|South Africa]] in the Round of 32 at the [[Beijing Science and Technology University Gymnasium]] on 11 August. In the one-minute-and-27-second match, Al Qubaisi was thrown onto the mat by August, who won by an [[Ippon]] score, preventing Al Qubaisi from advancing further.<ref name=\"QuabisiDefeatGulf\">{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/judo-al-qubaisi-s-early-exit-1.457514|title=Judo: Al Qubaisi\u2019s early exit|date=11 August 2008|newspaper=Gulf News|accessdate=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928003406/https://gulfnews.com/sport/judo-al-qubaisi-s-early-exit-1.457514|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live|agency=XPRESS}}</ref><ref name=\"BusinessQuabisiLoss\">{{cite news|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/uae-teenager-misses-out-in-beijing-judo-45285.html|title=UAE teenager misses out in Beijing judo|last=Sambridge|first=Andy|date=11 August 2008|newspaper=Arabian Business|accessdate=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928173548/https://www.arabianbusiness.com/uae-teenager-misses-out-in-beijing-judo-45285.html|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!scope=\"col\"|Round of 32\n!scope=\"col\"|Round of 16\n!scope=\"col\"|Quarterfinals\n!scope=\"col\"|Semifinals\n!scope=\"col\"|Repechage 1\n!scope=\"col\"|Repechage 2\n!scope=\"col\"|Repechage 3\n!colspan=2|Final / {{abbr|BM|Bronze medal match}}\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br/>Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Saeed Rashid Al Qubaisi]]\n|align=left|[[Judo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 73 kg|Men's \u221273 kg]]\n|align=center|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Marlon August|August]]|RSA|2008 Summer}} <br/> '''L''' 0000\u20131000\n|colspan=8|Did not advance<ref name=\"QuabisiDefeatGulf\" /><ref name=\"BusinessQuabisiLoss\" />\n|}\n\n==Sailing==\n{{main|Sailing at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\nAdil Mohammad was competing in his only Olympic Games and was 18 years old at the time of the Beijing Summer Olympics.<ref name=AdilSR>{{cite web|title=Adil Mohammad Bio, Stats, and Results|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mo/adil-mohammad-1.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701105913/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mo/adil-mohammad-1.html|archive-date=1 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was the first sailor from an Arab country to compete in the sport at the Olympics.<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> Mohammad qualified to take part in the [[Sailing at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Laser|men's laser sailing category]] after he was granted a wild card invitation by the Tripartite Commission.<ref name=mohammad-oly>{{cite news|first=Alaric|last=Gomes|title=Adel Khalid hopes for boost to his sport|url=http://gulfnews.com/sport/sailing/adel-khalid-hopes-for-boost-to-his-sport-1.643111|newspaper=Gulf News|date=19 June 2010|accessdate=9 July 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710090836/http://gulfnews.com/sport/sailing/adel-khalid-hopes-for-boost-to-his-sport-1.643111|archive-date=10 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He trained and competed in sailing competitions across Europe for seven months as preparation for the Games.<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> Before the Olympics, Mohammad spoke of his pride of representing the United Arab Emirates at the Olympics and stated he felt confident about winning the gold medal in his category: \"It is the dream of every athlete and sportsperson to compete in the Olympics. So it has been my dream as well. Now that I am going to Beijing, I feel proud of myself, I feel proud for my country and I hope to put the UAE on top of the world.\"<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> He competed in the one-person dinghy event, where he was assessed using a score derived from his participation in nine distinct races.<ref name=AdilSR/> In the first and second races, Mohammed finished 38th; in the third, 42nd; in the fourth, 43rd (and last); in the fifth, 11th (his highest); in the sixth, 36th; in the seventh, 42nd; in the eighth, 38th; and in the ninth, 27th. A tenth race was scheduled but cancelled.<ref name=\"ESPNSailing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=734|title=2008 Summer Olympics Results \u2013 Sailing \u2013 Men's \u2013 One person Dingy Results|publisher=ESPN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928173548/http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=734|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref> Overall, he ranked 42nd out of 43 sailors, earning a collective 272 points across all nine races.<ref name=ESPNSailing/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=11|Race\n!rowspan=2|Net points\n!rowspan=2|Final rank\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|1\n!scope=\"col\"|2\n!scope=\"col\"|3\n!scope=\"col\"|4\n!scope=\"col\"|5\n!scope=\"col\"|6\n!scope=\"col\"|7\n!scope=\"col\"|8\n!scope=\"col\"|9\n!scope=\"col\"|10\n!scope=\"col\"|M*\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Adil Mohammad]]\n|align=left|[[Sailing at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Laser|Laser]]\n|38\n|38\n|42\n|<s>43</s>\n|11\n|36\n|42\n|38\n|27\n|CAN\n|EL\n|272\n|42<ref name=\"ESPNSailing\" />\n|}\n<small>'''M''' = Medal race; EL = Eliminated \u2013 did not advance into the medal race; CAN = Race cancelled;</small>\n\n==Shooting==\n{{main|Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[File:Sheikh saeed bin maktoum al maktoum.jpg|thumb|right|Saeed Al Maktoum ''(pictured in 2016)'' represented the United Arab Emirates for the third time in Olympic shooting competition.]]\n\nThe oldest member of the team at the age of 44,<ref name=NIEAhmad>{{cite news|title=Al-Maktoum gearing up to defend his Olympic gold|url=http://www.newindpress.com/NewsItems.asp?ID=IEE20080730052916&Page=E&Title=Olympics+2008&Topic=0|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=15 August 2008|accessdate=27 September 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5a52tOwCe?url=http://www.newindpress.com/NewsItems.asp?ID%3DIEE20080730052916%26Page%3DE%26Title%3DOlympics%2B2008%26Topic%3D0|archivedate=15 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sheikh Ahmad Al-Makotum was making his third appearance at a Summer Olympiad, having previously represented the United Arab Emirates at the [[United Arab Emirates at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Summer Olympics]] and the [[United Arab Emirates at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Athens Olympic Games]].<ref name=\"ClayMay16\">{{cite news|url=http://www.clay-shooting.com/features/man-on-fire-how-royalty-in-the-uae-changed-britains-olympic-medal-future/|title=Man on fire \u2013 how royalty in the UAE changed Britain\u2019s Olympic-medal future|date=3 May 2016|newspaper=Clay Shooting|accessdate=27 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928173548/http://www.clay-shooting.com/features/man-on-fire-how-royalty-in-the-uae-changed-britains-olympic-medal-future/|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He won the nation's first gold medal in [[Shooting at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double trap|men's double trap]] at the 2004 Summer Olympics.<ref name=ClayMay16/> Ahmad Al-Makotum qualified for the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's trap|men's trap]] and [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double trap|double trap]] after winning two quota spots reserved by the [[International Shooting Sport Federation]] for athletes who met the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|minimum qualification scores]] of 112 and 118 points at the [[2005 World Shotgun Championships]] in [[Lonato del Garda]], Italy.<ref name=ClayMay16/><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.beijing2008.cn/upload/Qualification/issf_detailed_e.pdf|title=Games of the XXIX Olympiad, Beijing 2008: Shooting: International Shooting Sport Federation (ISSF)|date=December 2006|publisher=Olympic.org|pages=2\u20135|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815173850/http://en.beijing2008.cn/upload/Qualification/issf_detailed_e.pdf|archive-date=15 August 2008|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> He began his preparation for the Games two months beforehand,<ref name=NIEAhmad/> but said to ''[[The New Indian Express]]'' that he was not expecting to win anything in Beijing.<ref name=NIEAhmad/> On 9 August he competed in the qualification round of men's trap, finishing 30th out of 35 shooters with a score of 110. He equalled the score of [[Lee Wung Yew]] of [[Singapore at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Singapore]] and [[Ireland at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Ireland]]'s [[Derek Burnett]]. Ahmad Al-Makotum's tournament ended at the qualification round since he scored nine fewer points than the lowest-scoring qualifier.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Shooting at the 2008 Beijing Summer Games: Men's Trap Preliminary Round|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/2008/SHO/mens-trap-preliminary-round.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705110923/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/2008/SHO/mens-trap-preliminary-round.html|archive-date=5 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three days later, he took part in the qualifying round of the men's double trap, placing seventh out of nineteen competitors with a score of 136 points.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://cn.reuters.com/article/olympics-shooting-men-trap-qual-results-idCNISS83221320080812|title=Olympics-Shooting-Men's double trap qualification results|date=12 August 2008|access-date=29 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829083816/https://cn.reuters.com/article/olympics-shooting-men-trap-qual-results-idCNISS83221320080812|archive-date=29 August 2018|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> Ahmad Al-Makotum subsequently lost a four-way shoot-out to determine the sixth shooter to advance to the final between [[Australia at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Australia]]'s [[Russell Mark]], [[William Chetcuti]] of [[Malta at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Malta]] and [[Hungary at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Hungary]]'s [[Roland Gerebics]] since all four had the same score.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20080813/shooting/final-just-eludes-eighth-placed-chetcuti.220588|title=Final just eludes eighth-placed Chetcuti|date=13 August 2008|newspaper=[[Times of Malta]]|access-date=29 August 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816114357/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20080813/shooting/final-just-eludes-eighth-placed-chetcuti.220588|archive-date=16 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSheikh Saeed Al Maktoum was 31 years old at the time of the Beijing Olympics.<ref name=SaeedOverview>{{cite web|title=Sheikh Saeed Al-Maktoum Bio, Stats, and Results|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/sheikh-saeed-al-maktoum-1.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729051205/https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/sheikh-saeed-al-maktoum-1.html|archive-date=29 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also represented the United Arab Emirates at the 2000 Sydney Summer Games and the 2004 Athens Summer Olympics but did not medal.<ref name=SaeedOverview/> Saeed Al Maktoum earned automatic qualification for the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's skeet|men's skeet]] because he met the minimum qualification score of 114 points in the category at the [[2007 Asian Shooting Championships]] in [[Kuwait City]], Kuwait, where he won the bronze medal.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=SaeedXinhua>{{cite news|title=Dubai Crown Prince Al Maktoum Saeed eyes a medal at Olympics|url=http://www.china.org.cn/olympic/2008-07/30/content_16098413.htm|publisher=[[China Internet Information Center]]|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=30 July 2008|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219062541/http://www.china.org.cn/olympic/2008-07/30/content_16098413.htm|archive-date=19 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He began his training for his tournament after arriving in Beijing on 26 July.<ref name=SaeedXinhua/> Saeed Al Maktoum said of his chances, \"I have confidence in my capability, but I haven't got used to the shooting range yet. There are many ups and downs at the back (mountains). But in our country, the range is flat. We believe in God. If God gives you, nobody could take it away.\"<ref name=SaeedXinhua/> On 15 August he participated in the first heat of the qualification round of the men's skeet, finishing 22nd out of 41 participants with a score of 114 points.<ref name=\"ESPNMensSkeet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=298|title=2008 Summer Olympics Results \u2013 Shooting \u2013 Men's Skeet|publisher=ESPN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928043935/http://www.espn.com/oly/summer08/results?eventId=298|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref> He scored seven fewer points than the highest-scoring athlete, [[Vincent Hancock]] of the [[United States at the 2008 Summer Olympics|United States]], and four fewer than the lowest scoring qualifier, [[Qu Ridong]] of [[China at the 2008 Summer Olympics|China]]; his competition thus ended at the qualifying round.<ref name=ESPNMensSkeet/> He would again represent the United Arab Emirates at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] and the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio Olympics]].<ref name=SaeedOverview/>\n\n;Men\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=2|Qualification\n!colspan=2|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Points\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Points\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left rowspan=2|[[Ahmed Al-Maktoum (sport shooter)|Ahmad Al Maktoum]]\n|align=left|[[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's trap|Trap]]\n|110\n|30\n|colspan=2| Did not advance<ref name=\":4\" />\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double trap|Double trap]]\n|136\n|7\n|colspan=2| Did not advance<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Saeed bin Maktoum bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Saeed Al Maktoum]]\n|align=left|[[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's skeet|Skeet]]\n|114\n|22\n|colspan=2| Did not advance<ref name=\"ESPNMensSkeet\" />\n|}\n\n==Swimming==\n{{main|Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[File:InsideWatercube.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Beijing National Aquatics Centre]], where Al Jasmi took part in swimming contests.]]\n\n27-year-old police officer Obaid Al Jasmi was competing in his second Olympic Games after representing the United Arab Emirates four years earlier at the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens.<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> Although his best time of 53.70 seconds was 2.75 seconds slower than the \"B\" (FINA/Olympic) qualifying time for the event, he entered the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|men's 100 metres freestyle]] after being granted a universality place that was issued to swimmers who did not qualify on merit from the world governing body of swimming, [[FINA]].<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swimswam.com/fina-announces-qualifying-standards-for-london-2012/|title=FINA Announces Qualifying Standards for London 2012|last=Keith|first=Branden|date=25 November 2010|publisher=[[SwimSwam]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020001240/https://swimswam.com/fina-announces-qualifying-standards-for-london-2012/|archivedate=20 October 2016|access-date=17 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Environment\">{{cite web|url=http://fina.org/events/OG/Beijing_2008/pdf/qualifyingprocedures_sw.pdf|title=Olympic Qualifying Procedures for Swimming|publisher=[[FINA]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070304105903/http://www.fina.org/events/OG/Beijing_2008/pdf/qualifyingprocedures_sw.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=4 March 2007|accessdate=2007-03-20}}</ref> Al Jasmi had less than two months to prepare for the Games.<ref name=ALShinMag84/> He set himself the objective of improving his personal best time at the Olympics but noted the strong competition he would face.<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> On 12 August, Al Jasmi competed in the six-swimmer heat two of the contest.<ref name=Men100Freestyle>{{cite web|title=2008 Beijing Summer Olympics \u2013 Swimming \u2013 Men's 100m Freestyle|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/swimming/resultsandschedules/rsc=SWM011900/index.html|publisher=NBC Sports|accessdate=27 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517044815/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/swimming/resultsandschedules/rsc=SWM011900/index.html|archivedate=17 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He placed last with a new [[List of Emirates records in swimming|national-record]] time of 53.29 seconds.<ref name=ALShinMag84>{{cite journal|last=Gonzaga|first=Andre|title=Yet Another Olympic Games: More Lessons to be Learnt|url=https://www.alshindagah.com/Shindagah84/sport_1.htm|journal=Al Shindagah|issue=84|date=October 2008|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220025534/http://www.alshindagah.com/Shindagah84/sport_1.htm|archive-date=20 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Men100Freestyle/> Al Jasmi ranked 61st out of 64 swimmers overall and did not advance into the semi-finals since the format of the tournament only allowed for the progression of the top sixteen overall finishers.{{#tag:ref|One swimmer, [[Milorad \u010cavi\u0107]], withdrew from the tournament.<ref name=Men100Freestyle/>|group=\"n\"}}<ref name=Men100Freestyle/> After the Olympics, he spoke of his satisfaction of his performance: \"I benefited greatly from my participation in the Olympic Games and succeeded in bettering my personal record and I am looking forward to taking part in the GCC Championships and I am determined to achieve good results.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/swimming/obaid-keen-to-improve-form-1.125862|title=Obaid keen to improve form|last=Abbasher|first=Yasir|date=20 August 2008|newspaper=Gulf News|accessdate=27 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928003358/https://gulfnews.com/sport/swimming/obaid-keen-to-improve-form-1.125862|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n;Men\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=\"2\"|Heat\n!colspan=\"2\"|Semifinal\n!colspan=\"2\"|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Time\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Time\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n!scope=\"col\"|Time\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Obaid Al-Jasmi|Obaid Al Jasmi]]\n|align=left|[[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]\n|53.29 '''[[List of Emirates records in swimming|NR]]'''\n|61\n|colspan=4|Did not advance<ref name=\"ALShinMag84\" /><ref name=\"Men100Freestyle\" />\n|}\n\n==Taekwondo==\n{{main|Taekwondo at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n\nShaikka Maitha Al Maktoum was 28 years old at the time of the Beijing Summer Olympics and was making her debut appearance in the Olympic Games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maitha Al-Maktoum Bio, Stats, and Results|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/maitha-al-maktoum-1.html|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=27 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708042333/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/al/maitha-al-maktoum-1.html|archive-date=8 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She was announced as a qualified competitor for the [[Taekwondo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 67 kg|women's middleweight (\u221267kg) taekwondo competition]] after the IOC cleared her to participate following the allocation of quota places for athletes deemed to have \"an extraordinary record in their sporting discipline.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Gomes|first=Alaric|title=Shaika Maitha bound for Beijing Olympics|url=http://archive.gulfnews.com/indepth/olympics08/sports/10199968.html|newspaper=Gulf Times|date=24 March 2008|accessdate=27 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620232311/http://archive.gulfnews.com/indepth/olympics08/sports/10199968.html|archivedate=20 June 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Maitha Al Maktoum trained at the [[Kyung Hee University]] in the South Korean capital city of [[Seoul]] to prepare for the Games.<ref name=\"KTPrincess\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/people/2013/08/178_28790.html|title=UAE Princess Will Compete in Taekwondo at Beijing Olympics|last=Se-jeong|first=Kim|date=5 August 2008|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929090302/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/people/2013/08/178_28790.html|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She said before the Olympics, \"Everybody who is going to compete in Beijing is going there to win and I am no exception. I have to respect them all. They have all dedicated themselves to this and the only thing they want is a medal. I am the same though and I will have to match their focus if I am to succeed.\"<ref name=\"EmiratesAOverview\"/> Maitha Al Maktoum faced [[South Korea at the 2008 Summer Olympics|South Korea]]'s [[Hwang Kyung-seon]] in the Round of 16 on 22 August. She lost to her opponent 5\u20131 in points and was defeated 4\u20130 in her [[repechage]] match against [[Sandra \u0160ari\u0107]] of [[Croatia at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Croatia]], ending her chance of a bronze medal.<ref name=\"MatchShaikka\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/uae-sheikha-kicked-in-her-face-in-taekwondo-debut-295590.html|title=UAE sheikha kicked in her face in taekwondo debut|date=22 August 2008|accessdate=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929090548/https://www.news18.com/news/india/uae-sheikha-kicked-in-her-face-in-taekwondo-debut-295590.html|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live|publisher=[[CNN-News18]]}}</ref> After the tournament, Matiha Al Maktoum stated, \"It's a dream and a nightmare at the same time. I couldn't wait until it was going to happen. And now I can't believe it's over. I think I performed well for what my background is and my experience.\"<ref name=MatchShaikka/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!scope=\"col\"|Round of 16\n!scope=\"col\"|Quarterfinals\n!scope=\"col\"|Semifinals\n!scope=\"col\"|Repechage \n!scope=\"col\"|Bronze Medal\n!colspan=2|Final\n|-style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Opposition<br />Result\n!scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Maitha bint Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Maitha Al Maktoum]]\n|align=left|[[Taekwondo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 67 kg|Women's \u221267 kg]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Hwang Kyung-Seon|Hwang K-S]]|KOR|2008 Summer}}<br/>'''L''' 1\u20135\n|colspan=2|Did not advance\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Sandra \u0160ari\u0107|\u0160ari\u0107]]|CRO|2008 Summer}}<br/> '''L''' 0\u20134\n|colspan=3|Did not advance<ref name=\"MatchShaikka\" />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[United Arab Emirates at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|30em|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Nations at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Portal bar|Olympics|United Arab Emirates}}\n\n[[Category:Nations at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:United Arab Emirates at the Summer Olympics by year|2008]]\n[[Category:2008 in Emirati sport|Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "Usernameunique", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaekwondo:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Arab_Emirates_at_the_2008_Summer_Olympics"}
